column168: UPRR employee reported a strong odor emitting from bowl track 40, Roseville Yard, with LPG tank cars. TILX 308616 was found with an odor coming from the protective housings. TILX 308616: ?A end? Liquid Valve was partially open; the plug was tool tight but did not create a seal. 1 liquid cup of LPG released from the plug threads. Closing the valve stopped the release. The plug threads were cleaned, new Teflon was applied, and the plug was secured to the valve. Old Seal 00048872, New Seal 0000282.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XWK experienced a UN1791 Dynachlor release from (4) 55-gallon poly drums. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 4-ounces of product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the pallet and drums due to the vent caps releasing as a possible cause of temperature changes/drum expansion. The four drums in shipment and the impacted pallet were wiped down and neutralized with a vinegar solution. All caps were replaced, and the drums were secured for shipment on. All impacted rags, and the damaged caps were placed into a 10-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: XPO Logistics Terminal NKX experienced a UN2801 Keyazine Brown MO/LA Liquid release from a 275-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 3 ounces of product released to a 1’ x 1’ area of the tote body and trailer floor due to a loose cap. The cap was re-secured, and the impacted tote and trailer floor were wiped down and neutralized with a soda ash solution. A slosh test was conducted on the tote and verified the tote could be shipped on. The impacted rags were containerized into a 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: IT was reported a one-cup spill of UN3288 "ZINC CHROMATE CZ20" that arrived damaged at Terminal NCH. The caller stated that (1) a 55-pound paper bag was damaged due to freight impact as a result of a load shift impacting Trailer #321-6239. The contractor arrived and noted the material was spilled inside of the trailer and left a trail leading out onto the dock where the pallet containing the damaged bag was. The contractor was able to confirm the dock plate prevented any material from releasing onto the ground beneath the trailer. The pallet was restacked; the damaged bag and released material were placed into (1) 55-poly drum. The waste was left onsite for the terminal to manage.

column168: At approximately 09:00 on Friday, November 3, 2023, a Basic Chemicals truck driver was delivering Hydrochloric Acid to a customer site (AZZ Inc.) located in Prairie Grove, AR. When the driver began to offload product they immediately noticed the cam-lock connection at the customers connection was dripping, so they shut down the process, cleared the line and shimmed the cam-lock ears. The driver resumed unloading a second time and noticed the fitting continued to drip so they closed the internal valve on top of the tanker trailer and replaced the gasket at the cam-lock connection. When the driver reopened the internal valve, product was released from the CPVC piping system that is connected to the internal valve of the trailer. Approximately 2 cups of product was release and spilled. No injuries or damage to equipment was reported.
column169: The driver waited for a 3rd party repair company to arrive at the customer site and make necessary repairs to the tanker trailer. The repair company arrived on-site and discovered a damaged CPVC fitting in the piping system that contributed to the minimum release of product. The repair company made the necessary repairs to the trailer and the driver was then able to safely offload the product into the customer storage tank.  This incident was reviewed with the driver by their supervisor so the driver fully understood the cause for the CPVC piping failure. Existing offloading procedures were discussed to ensure driver's understanding.
column172: Tank truck, tank mounted on truck chassis

column168: At approximately 09:00 AM a Basic Chemicals truck driver was delivering Caustic Soda to a customer site (Mosaic) located in St. James, LA. The driver met with the customer site operator, completed the “In the Interest of Safety Form” (which is a form utilized by Basic Chemical truck drivers to ensure that enough space exists in a customer tank prior to unloading), hooked up offloading hoses, and began offloading. Near the end of offloading, the driver knew the tanker trailer was getting close to being empty, so he got with the customer site operator to check the level of the storage tank again to ensure there was enough room remaining in the product storage tank. The operator checked the level of the storage tank and confirmed with the driver that there was enough space to complete the offload. Not long after the customer site operator left the area the storage tank began to overflow and the Basic Chemicals truck driver immediately shut down the flow of product. The driver got with the customer site operator to notify him of the overflow and the operator stated that the tank level indicator had been malfunctioning lately. Customer site personnel were able to clean up the spill which was estimated to be approximately 20 gallons. No injuries or damage to equipment was reported.
column169: The Basic Chemicals truck driver immediately shut down the offloading operation and notified customer site operators. The area was washed down and cleaned up. Occidental Chemical Tech Service group has been requested to reach out to the customer site (Mosaic) to discuss necessary corrections that are needed moving forward to prevent a re-occurrence. Proper repairs/replacement need to be completed to the level indicator on the product storage tank at the customer site.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal XFM experienced a UN3066 Sika Floor 161-264 Part B release from a 1-gallon metal can. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of material released to a 15’ x 8’ area of the trailer floor due to a forklift puncture. The damaged pail was containerized into a double lined 55-gallon metal drum. Soda ash and absorbents were then deployed to neutralize and clean the impacted area. All impacted absorbents and impacted pallet pieces were then containerized into a second double lined 55-gallon metal drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On November 14, 2023, one (1) 275-gallon tote of paint was crushed in transit and released approximately one and a half (1.5) gallons of product to the loading dock floor and pallet. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Moran Environmental Recovery (MER) to remediate the impacted site. Crews utilized hand tools to scrape the released product off the loading dock floor. MER personnel utilized absorbent pads with a degreasing agent to collect any residual product from the impacted areas. Crews then utilized a rotary transfer pump to transfer the contents of the damaged 275-gallon tote to a new 275-gallon tote to be shipped off to its destination. MER personnel deployed granular absorbents inside the damaged tote, to solidify any remaining product, once the rotary transfer pump stopped. Crews then placed absorbent pads, under the damaged tote, and wrapped the tote in two (2) layers of poly sheeting to ensure any additional residual product was contained. All UN1263 impacted material was collected and containerized in two (2) 55-gallon drums for disposal by R+L.

column168: On November 20, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of UN2810 fell off the lift gate and released approximately one (1) gallon of product to the trailer interior and pavement below. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from GrayMar Environmental (GME) to remediate the impacted site.  GME personnel utilized hand tools, absorbents, and soda ash to remediate the UN2810-impacted trailer and roadway. All impacted material was collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum and one (1) 95-gallon overpack and taken to the R+L terminal for disposal.

On November 20, 2023, one (1) 55-gallond drum containing UN3264 was punctured by a forklift and released approximately ten (10) gallons of product to the trailer interior and dock floor. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from First Call Environmental (FCE) to remediate the impacted site. FCE personnel deployed granular absorbents to the sulfuric acid solution-impacted trailer interior and swept them in with hand tools. All spent absorbents and excess debris were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon drum for transport and disposal.

XPO Logistics terminal UPO experienced a release from a box containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations.  Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1 ounce of material released to the packaging/container only. The cap of one 1-gallon poly jug was crushed causing a release. The damaged jug was removed from the box and containerized along with PPE into a 15-gallon poly jug. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
